The Artist

Charles Rencountre

A member of the Sicańġu people from the Lower Brule Reservation in South Dakota, Charles Rencountre is a sculptor whose monumental works stand as testaments to Indigenous resilience, water protection, and the enduring power of Lakota ceremony.

Graduated top of his class from the Institute of American Indian Arts in Santa Fe, his most celebrated work — the eight-foot reinforced concrete sculpture “Not Afraid to Look” — remains the only physical evidence of the ten-month gathering of Water Protectors at Standing Rock. Together with his wife and collaborator Alicia Rencountre-Da Silva, their vision extends “Not Afraid to Look” as a global symbol of strength for people fighting to protect natural resources.

Milestones

Exhibitions & Installations

2024

Giiwedinong Museum, Park Rapids MN

“Not Afraid to Look” permanent installation with opening ceremony and community gathering

2018

UMN Duluth — “Making Art That Speaks Truth to Power”

Lecture and community engagement on monument building as a vehicle for social change

2016

Sacred Stone Camp, Standing Rock

Erected “Not Afraid to Look” during the NO DAPL water protector gathering on the Missouri River

2014

Institute of American Indian Arts, Santa Fe

First installation of “Not Afraid to Look” — graduated top of class

Ongoing

“Mixed Medicines” Traveling Exhibition

Collaboration with Ledger artist Dwayne Wilcox (Oglala Sioux) addressing the impact of substance abuse on traditional Lakota ceremonies
